</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Rashere (SONY) wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Our suggested changes are just one of the ways we can go about this goal and we posted them specifically to get your feedback.  It's not set in stone and there are always other options.
<br />

<br />
- There's always the status quo.  We could make no changes and leave things as they are.  I don't think this is really a good solution, though, since it doesn't do anything to address charm being a usable day-to-day ability. 
<br />

<br />
- We could go back to the method used before Omens, remove the mitigation, and make the majority of NPCs non-charmable.  Again, this really doesn't help charm's usability at all. 
<br />

<br />
- We can make changes only to the newer areas that have charm mitigation and leave everything else alone.  We would not be able to make any global-level changes such as altering charm spells, though.  It would also leave all of the restrictions on charm throughout the game intact.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody"></span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
