                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">My original post still stands, to clarify a bit.
<br />

<br />
Make charm overwrite all benficial buffs on a mob. This prevents anyone from mezzing it, or rooting it and loading it with buffs prior to charming.
<br />

<br />
Detrimental dots/slows etc stay as well as DD spells will land to allow normal melee and damage to the mob.  Attackers are not going to heal their enemy or provide beneficial buffing. So this theory may work.  
<br />

<br />
Leave the Mob at 100% DPS.  dont nerf it, but you cant buff the hell out it either.
<br />

<br />
While charm is in effect on a mob, its immune to all beneficial spells (buffing)
<br />

<br />
This is in line with the game play..  and what I believe would be an easier solution than reworking entire mob tables.
<br />

<br />
As for confusing this with a nerf.. think of it this way, you get 100% DPS from your mob, not the current 20-25%, no extra exp penalty, you know what damage its gonna do to you when charm breaks, healers/tanks etc must be ready to keep you alive while you attempt to re-charm the mob as well as deal with other mobs in camp.
<br />

<br />
The Risk vs Reward has been restored. 
<br />
The DSP on the mob has been restored.
<br />
The Exp has been restored.
<br />

<br />
Not being able to insanely buff a charmed pet should satisfy SOE as well as Enchanters not being penalized for doing our job and go a LONG way to address the balance issue.
<br />

<br />
No major mob table re-writes for SOE, meaning we get this quicker.
<br />

<br />
(I've been playing an Enchanter since Beta, I'm not a noob wanting uber solo capabilities.)
<br />

<br />
Aurbo SkyeFyre
<br />
Kane Bayle</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
