                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Ok, I added this to eq forums:
<br />

<br />
Rashere,
<br />
 
<br />
Essentially, we are talking about Control.  The only way charm will be viable in groups and raids; is by if the group/raid believes the enchanter can control their pet.  Random charm breaks with a charmed pet that does not produce outstanding dps during charm but can wipe a raid, will not and currently is not tolerated by groups.  They refuse to let chanters charm(or mez in some cases but you are attempting to work on that aspect of chanter CC).
<br />
 
<br />
So if the risk is too great, Enchanters have to prove to groups they can Control their pet.  How?
<br />
 
<br />
1.  Dire charm update.(Currently the dmg. table in use if spread to the rest of Norrath would mean we might as well just be able to dire charm any given mob in any given zone with the current dmg table used as the deciding factor.){Side note:  ADC would not be overpowerful...so what if the charmed pet does a slight %increase over that of other pet classes...the other pet classes far outshine the dps any enchanter could do one on one and they know it.}
<br />
 
<br />
2.  Total Domination update.(This AA has to allow an enchanter to hold a mob under charm the duration of the spell without random brks for it to be a viable solution.  Groups need to know we have control or forget it.  The first random brk and no more charming in that group.  Also if we go this route some sort of dmg table increase through focus/haste etc to create more dps in line with rest of the group--if dps equals an enchanters animation, their is no reason to charm.  Also if we have to keep recharming the pet -- that risk is reason alone for the added dps.)
<br />
 
<br />
3.  Note I am refering to charming with your avg group...not one geared toward reverse charm, which is becoming a classic solo technique but many groups do not understand this style.  Which brings up pt 3:  Rule of 4 must be gone.  A classic group does not want to change its style to accomidate a charmed pet that can not compete with your avg dps player.
<br />
 
<br />
4. Experience penalty must be removed, which you stated is possible.
<br />
 
<br />
5.  Multi-pet charm   no reason this could not happen see spirit call shaman AA.(ok  I threw that one in, but it would be really cool to charm more than one mob--if we are on the standard oow dmg table, one way to add dps is to add multiple mobs under charm for short duration(not variable).)
<br />

<br />
Obviously,  the devs will have to lets us have a look at the true dmg table they have created for Charmed Norrathian mobs, before any true discussion on how much control we will be given over any particular mob ie will the dmg table justify an enchanter even to charm?--- will the dps be that much greater than his animation?---will groups believe the dps of a charmed pet is even worth the mana cast?
<br />
 
<br />
So we will really need some hard numbers of the dps of a charmed pet very soon, if we are all to come to some form of concensus on whether we are talking ADC, Total Dom or just plain variable charm.  Those numbers will make the choice  relative to any further discussion.
<br />

<br />
Rashere,
<br />
 
<br />
*"There's always the status quo.  We could make no changes and leave things as they are.  I don't think this is really a good solution, though, since it doesn't do anything to address charm being a usable day-to-day ability."
<br />
Is this dps 20% of the mobs potetial dps, if so no group will charm or raid, unless full control of pet ie adc is involved.
<br />

<br />
*"We could go back to the method used before Omens, remove the mitigation, and make the majority of NPCs non-charmable.  Again, this really doesn't help charm's usability at all."
<br />
Obviously 100% dps...many want this type of charm but as you say there wont be much to charm.
<br />

<br />
*"We can make changes only to the newer areas that have charm mitigation and leave everything else alone.  We would not be able to make any global-level changes such as altering charm spells, though.  It would also leave all of the restrictions on charm throughout the game intact."
<br />
This pt. resembes pt one.
<br />

<br />
If we decide to make changes, we need to know what % dmg of the total charmed pets output you are thinking.  Also is there a cap, ie if we decide to add haste, focus effect etc. will that dps be capped. 
<br />

<br />
Again, I can not say enough, if we are dealing with a dmg table that is less than 75-80% of the mobs total output, no group will let a chanter use charm in its current form.  More control of the pet will be necessarry.  How much control depends upon how much dps you are willing to allow the pet to have, ie: in its present form, groups will settle for no less than an adc'd pet...since the dps output is not worth the hassle of dealling with a pet that brks charm randomly.(think of it this way:  currently if a bst or mage can not control thier pet durring a raid...they are asked to kill that pet.)</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
