                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I just added my two cents on the Sony forums.  Remember it's just my view so please don't burn me too much with flames - slight blistering of the skin is ok, but no black charring or worse yet, skin melted off to the bone !  Here is the post.
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">  This will be my first post so forgive me if it rambles some.  Basic background.  I started an enchanter several years ago - Kunark Expansion - partly on RL friends behalf and partly on the abilities of an enchanter at the time.  I couldn't wait to get charm.  Charm was great, I could use it to solo and I could use it in groups to turn the battle to our favor.  The main reasons for this as I see(n) them were 1) I could stop the damage of one NPC against the group or myself and turn it against another 2) I could  control the ex-charmed NPC about 90% of the time by myself upon charm break.  Yes it was - and is still - very focus intense to do, but it was also fun, well when I didn't die it was fun. Groups didn't seem to mine that I would die on ocassion if it meant that the majority of the time it was a benefit.  This was pre-exp penalty for using a charmed pet.  This in and of itself wasn't a killer of charming.  A lot of enchanters stopped charming when the ability for the enchanter to control the pet on charm break was reduce by 1) the enchanter's lack of new spells to help get the ex-charmed pet under control and 2) the scaling of NPC damage.  I managed to get to level 56 with my enchanter and now I find it extremely hard to make any progress because my animation just doesn't put out enough damage to be useful in a solo situation, and while I can still charm in older zones I lack the ability to regain control of the ex-charmed pet.  Now I'm not saying I want to have the ability to gain control 100% of the time - that would not be fun or fair to any other class, but what I would like to see is at least a 60% chance to regain control or get enough time to get my speed bump self at a safer distance.  I know this doesn't sound like it has anything to to with the topic, but please be patient with me here.  Most of the post here have talked about the survivablity of the enchanter and the group after charm break and have had some creative sugguestions - most I don't believe would lead to a class inbalance. So in keeping on the topic and the sugguestions here is my own thoughts on charming and the proposed changes and what I think could be used to go with them.
<br />
  I actually like the idea of a charm that would include buffs that enchanters usually use; however, I see the point of others not wanting someone choosing the buffs for them.  I personnaly did haste my charmed pets, but not always with the best haste spell available - I don't like being paste of the cavern floor.  That said I still like the idea as proposed, charm with a haste, strength, and AC buff - especially the proposal of having these buffs dispelling upon charm break.  When I charmed - like most enchanters - would break the charm with dispell to get the buffs off the ex-charmed NPC.  Of course this meant I had to have the buffs and the dispells loaded in my spell set and didn't give me a lot of options for the remaining spells, mostly control spell and maybe a direct damage spell.  Having charm with buffs would free up spell slots that I could use for break control spells - hopefully some new or redesigned (ie faster cast, higher level affected) spells.  Others have made a very good point about charm breaks and I would like to add to them.  Keeping with the idea of charm - where the NPC is taken control of an coecered to do our bidding for a time - I think the sugguestion of a befuddled/confused state upon charm break would be right in the story line of the ability.  I believe it would be reasonable to conclude an NPC would have a few moments of questioning what just happened and who did this to me.  My sugguestion is to go with the proposed change of charm with buffs, dispelling upon break, and add a 1 to 2 tick confused state.  Along with that though I have to make the unpopular sugguestion that when the NPC does gain control of his wits, he is bent on getting revenge on the enchanter above all others. That would be a fair conclusion to make of an NPC's behavior and if we are given re-designed/new spells to help bring our chances of regaining control over the NPC to about 60-70% I hink the Risk verses Reward would be a little more acceptable from the group and enchanters point of view - if the exp penalty was done away with and the NPC's damage was scaled up to say 60-70% of it's normal DPS.
<br />
  Bottom line to all this rambling, I could fine the proposed change to charm acceptable IF we would get 1) better DPS (60-70% of normal), the exp penalty was taken off, and we were given a 60-70% chance of surviving charm breaks with new spells and a confused state of 1-2 ticks.  I would gladly accept the fact that the NPC is coming straight for me if I fail to regain control - they usually do with few exceptions.  Whatever the decision of SOE I hope you will figure this out and make playing an enchanter fun, exciting, and balanced .</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody"></span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />Everquest - It's life, Captain, but not life as we know it.
<br />
Commander Spock, <span style="font-style: italic">Star Trek I The Movie</span>
<br />

